SIMPLE: nothing
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nothing
<hw>Noth"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>no</ets>,
a. + <ets>thing</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not anything; no thing
(in the widest sense of the word <xex>thing</xex>); -- opposed to
<ant>anything</ant> and <ant>something</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet had his aspect <qex>nothing</qex> of severe.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Nonexistence; nonentity; absence of being; nihility;
nothingness.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A thing of no account, value, or note; something
irrelevant and impertinent; something of comparative unimportance; utter
insignificance; a trifle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Behold, ye are of <qex>nothing</qex>, and your work of nought.</q>
<rj><qau>Is. xli. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is <qex>nothing</qex>, says the fool; but, says the friend,⟦br⟧
This <qex>nothing</qex>, sir, will bring you to your end.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Arith.)</fld> <def>A cipher; naught.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nothing but</b></col>, <cd>only; no more than.</cd>
<au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>To make nothing of</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To make no difficulty of; to consider as trifling or important.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧We are industrious to preserve our bodies from slavery, but we
<xex>make nothing of</xex> suffering our souls to be slaves to our
lusts.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ray.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Not to understand; <as>as,
I could <ex>make nothing of</ex> what he said</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nothing</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nothing
<hw>Noth"ing</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In no degree; not at all; in no
wise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Adam, with such counsel <qex>nothing</qex> swayed.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The influence of reason in producing our passions is
<qex>nothing</qex> near so extensive as is commonly believed.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nothing off</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>an order to
the steersman to keep the vessel close to the wind.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nothingarian</ent>⟦br⟧
